 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fdcec141-6da8-4dc1-8410-2e994debbf56",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let the pretest odds of having a disease be 1 (so 50% chance of disease, half the\n",
    "people are infected)\n",
    "\n",
    "A test for the disease has:\n",
    "- Sensitivity=0.8,\n",
    "- Specificity=0.10\n",
    "\n",
    "**What is the post-test odds of disease, if test is negative? Show details of how you arrived at the answer.**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "652b340e-51fb-427a-8c41-a74fcf2995cc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can use Bayes theorum to answer this question.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The pre-test odds are 1: 0.5 (disease) / 1 - 0.5 (no disease)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "LR = (1 - sensitivity)/ specificity = 1 -0.8 / 0.1 = 2\n",
    "\n",
    "Post-test odds = pre-test odds  * LR = 1 * 2 = **2**\n",
    "\n",
    "The post test odds of disease increase to 2 after a negative test result.\n",
    "This is suprising because that means after receiving a negative test result the odds of the person having the disease are even higher (despite the negative result)\n",
    "\n",
    "The low specificity means the test frequently gives a false negative for people without the diesease. When specificity is very low, even a negative test result can paradoxically increase the odds of disease. This highlights how important it is for clinicians to evaluate the effectiveness of a test before using it, especially in screening programs, where false results (false negatives or false positives) can lead to harmful outcomes."
   ]
  },
